//! Linux native AIO (libaio) subsystem.
//!
//! # Scope
//!
//! This module backs the five Linux *native* AIO syscalls used by the LTP
//! `aio*` cases (`aio01`, `aio02`, `aiocp`, `aiodio_*`, `aio-stress`):
//!
//! ```text
//!   io_setup(nr_events, &ctx)            -> create a context   [sys_io_setup]
//!   io_submit(ctx, n, iocbpp)            -> submit n requests  [sys_io_submit]
//!   io_getevents(ctx, min, n, events, t) -> reap completions   [sys_io_getevents]
//!   io_cancel(ctx, iocb, result)         -> cancel a request   [sys_io_cancel]
//!   io_destroy(ctx)                      -> tear down a context [sys_io_destroy]
//! ```
//!
//! These are the kernel `io_*` syscalls (POSIX `aio_read`/`aio_write` are a
//! glibc userspace-thread emulation and do **not** reach here).
//!
//! # Execution model: simulated async (for now)
//!
//! We currently run a **synchronous-at-submit** model: [`SyncEngine::submit`]
//! performs the I/O inline and produces a completed [`IoEvent`] immediately,
//! which `io_submit` queues on the context. `io_getevents` then just drains
//! that queue. This is correct for libaio (results are simply ready by the
//! time the caller reaps them) and is the standard minimal-kernel approach.
//!
//! The [`AioEngine`] trait is the seam for a *real* async implementation later:
//! a future engine would enqueue the request, return `None` (nothing ready
//! yet), and complete it from a worker / DMA-completion path, pushing the
//! `IoEvent` onto the context's queue out-of-band. The registry, context
//! lifecycle, and the `io_getevents` drain logic stay unchanged.
//!
//! # Context identity
//!
//! `io_setup` writes an opaque `aio_context_t` token back to userspace. libaio
//! treats that token as a pointer to a userspace `aio_ring` and, in
//! `io_getevents`, peeks `ring->magic`; only when it equals `AIO_RING_MAGIC`
//! does it read events from userspace directly, otherwise it falls back to the
//! `io_getevents` *syscall*. We deliberately keep the token a plain opaque id
//! (its `magic` is whatever happens to be there, never our value), so libaio
//! always takes the syscall path and our queue is authoritative.
//!
//! TODO(real-ring): to support libaio's zero-syscall fast path we would
//! instead `mmap` a real `aio_ring` page into the process and mirror events
//! into it. Not needed while we force the syscall fallback.

extern crate alloc;

use alloc::collections::{BTreeMap, VecDeque};
use alloc::sync::Arc;
use core::sync::atomic::{AtomicU64, Ordering};

